{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17652178","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17652178"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:33:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:33:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18517"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18517","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18517"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.3,0.09,0.13,0.43,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11246"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76378"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11246","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11246"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18517"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61887"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7427"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26069"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26314"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76378","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76378"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe iliacus muscle is a key component of the iliopsoas muscle group and plays an important role in hip movement.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the anatomical attachments of the iliacus muscle?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Greater trochanter to iliac crest","Iliac crest to pubic tubercle","Iliac spine to lateral condyle of the tibia","Iliac fossa to lesser trochanter","Lesser trochanter to pubic ramus"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eiliac fossa to lesser trochanter\u003C/strong\u003E correctly describes the attachments of the iliacus muscle. The muscle originates from the superior two-thirds of the iliac fossa and inserts into the lesser trochanter of the femur, joining with the psoas major muscle to form the iliopsoas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGreater trochanter to iliac crest\u003C/strong\u003E - These are the approximate attachments of the gluteus medius muscle\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIliac crest to pubic tubercle\u003C/strong\u003E - These are the approximate attachments of the internal oblique muscle\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIliac spine to lateral condyle of the tibia\u003C/strong\u003E - These are the approximate attachments of the tensor fasciae latae muscle\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELesser trochanter to pubic ramus\u003C/strong\u003E - This is not an anatomically correct muscle pathway\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe iliacus muscle is innervated by the femoral nerve (L2-L4) and functions primarily as a hip flexor. It works in conjunction with the psoas major muscle to flex the thigh at the hip joint and assists in lateral rotation of the thigh.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The iliacus muscle originates from the superior two-thirds of the iliac fossa and inserts into the lesser trochanter of the femur.","The iliacus muscle is innervated by the femoral nerve (L2-L4).","The primary action of the iliacus muscle is flexion of the hip joint, with a secondary action of lateral rotation."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","\u201cAnterior Hip Muscles\u201d by Beth ohara\u00a0is licensed under\u00a0Creative Commons Attribution-Share Alike 3.0 Unported license. (http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/). \u003Chttps://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Anterior_Hip_Muscles_2.PNG\u003E"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61887"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18517"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21413"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21413","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21413"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/mFDiJzxLwQ4d3FkGvDxXRAgxH5eoPk.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/mFDiJzxLwQ4d3FkGvDxXRAgxH5eoPk.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":960}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61887","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61887"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-03T11:49:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-03T17:56:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11246"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76378"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"